Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: sc03 THE BARN NET + sc06 THE SEIZURE — varsity core, one county, the mirror
Draft date: 2026-07-12 17:10

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A pull-cord CLICKS.

Light drops over the APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER. Hand-machined gauges sit crooked in a welded panel, each one filed and fitted by hand. A crew couch is bolted into a steel cradle below a triangular window.

The window looks out at a Moon painted on the barn boards, gray and cratered, taller than a man.

ALONG THE BACK WALL -- spiral notebooks stand floor to roof. Every spine is dated in the same block hand. The bottom shelf starts in 1972.

Folding chairs lean on a card table. A percolator sits cold on an upturned crate. The room is half flight facility and half clubhouse, and nobody who built it ever noticed the difference.

Headlights swing across the painted Moon and hold there.

Outside, a pickup rolls up the dirt drive and parks by the fence. A second set of lights follows it up. A third pulls in behind.

CRICKET DAWES -- 79, seed-corn cap, a wedding band he still turns with his thumb -- stands at the panel already, going down a checklist with a golf pencil.

The barn door rolls back. GUNNY TIBBS -- 71, Navy ballcap, a folded flag carried flat in both arms -- comes in first and sets the flag on the card table before he says a word.

GUNNY:
Percolator's cold, Cricket.

CRICKET:
It'll come up.

STITCH McGREW -- 74, a paper sack of something warm under one arm -- holds the door for the last man.

STITCH:
Brought kolaches. Sausage and the other kind.

DUTCH HAAS -- 76, a black ledger and a mechanical pencil, nothing else in his hands -- steps around him without looking at the sack.

DUTCH:
You bring 'em every week and I tell you every week I don't eat before a descent.

STITCH:
Yeah, I know. Bring 'em anyway.

GUNNY:
Headsets. We're eight minutes down.

The four of them take their chairs in a loose ring near the panel. They pull headsets on over their caps. Nobody moves more than a few feet apart.

Gunny keys his loop. His voice goes flat and formal.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Apollo Eighteen. Lunar descent rehearsal. Number two thousand, eight hundred and six.

He waits. He can hear Stitch breathing through eight feet of open air, and he waits for it on the loop anyway.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Stitch. Comm check.

STITCH (RADIO):
Loud and clear, Gun.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Say again.

STITCH (RADIO):
Loud and clear.

Cricket sets his hand on the throttle. The needles come alive on the panel.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Program's in. Coming up on high gate.

STITCH (RADIO):
You watch that thing last night? The landing?

DUTCH (RADIO):
We are on the loop.

STITCH (RADIO):
I know where we are. I'm asking did you watch it.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Four thousand feet.

STITCH (RADIO):
'Cause I watched it twice. Computer flew those two boys down, held both their hands the whole way, and he still come in long. Rolled right on past his own mark.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Nine hundred feet long. Not that it matters to your point.

STITCH (RADIO):
It don't matter to my point.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I know it don't. I'm putting the number right.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Three thousand. Coming down.

STITCH (RADIO):
And that fella's got a patch on his arm and a parade in Houston.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Loop discipline. Both of you.

A needle low on the panel takes a small drop. It comes back. Then it dips again and starts a slow walk downward.

DUTCH (RADIO):
(not looking up)
Bus B.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Confirm.

DUTCH (RADIO):
(reading his ledger)
It's that relay again. I wrote it up back in eighty-four. It's all in the book.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Steady or does it stutter?

DUTCH (RADIO):
It stutters. Give it a second and it'll drop again.

The needle jumps, hangs, jumps again.

DUTCH (RADIO):
There. Kick it. Low left corner.

Cricket brings the heel of his boot up under the panel and raps the low left corner once, without looking at it.

The needle climbs and settles home.

DUTCH (RADIO):
(a beat)
I've said for years it wants a new relay.

STITCH (RADIO):
You have said that.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I'm allowed to say it. It's my write-up.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Fifteen hundred feet.

STITCH (RADIO):
All I'm saying is, put either one of those boys from last night in that seat with a stuttering bus and no computer, and where do they set down.

DUTCH (RADIO):
They don't set down. Hell, they don't even clear the physical to get in the seat.

STITCH (RADIO):
Now that is the truth.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Seven hundred feet. Quiet on the loop.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Seven hundred. Down at twenty.

Cricket eases the throttle back. The barn is loud with three men who have opinions.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Three hundred feet.

Nobody says anything. Nobody reaches for a kolache. The room goes still on its own, and no one asked it to.

A blue CONTACT LIGHT blinks on the panel.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Contact light. Engine stop.

For one beat the barn holds nothing but the tick of the cooling percolator.

STITCH (RADIO):
(off the gauge)
Half a foot a second at the deck.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Little left of center.

CRICKET (RADIO):
On the line.

They pull the headsets down around their necks. The room comes back to room volume.

GUNNY:
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

CRICKET:
God willing.

Stitch is already up, tearing the sack open on the card table. The percolator starts to knock.

STITCH:
Sausage or the other kind, Gun.

GUNNY:
The other kind. And leave the flag be, you've got grease on you.

DUTCH:
He flew it long and they gave him a parade.

STITCH:
Let it go, Dutch.

DUTCH:
I let it go. I'm just saying it once more and then I'm done with it.

Cricket pours four cups and does not sit down with them. He carries his to the panel and opens a fresh notebook.

He writes in ballpoint block letters, pressing hard. T+2,806. BUS B CORRECTED. CONTACT 19:41. CREW PRESENT.

One truck cranks outside. Then another.

GUNNY:
You want the flag inside or on the porch pole tonight.

CRICKET:
Porch is fine.

The three of them go out. Cricket runs a thumb down the dated spines on the back wall on his way to the door, slow, the whole shelf, and does not stop on any one of them.

Taillights swing around in the yard and shrink down the drive, one behind the other, and turn onto the section road.

Cricket rolls the barn door shut and tests the padlock with one pull.

Past the yard the farmhouse stands square against the sky with no lights on inside it.

He stands in the dark a moment, then starts across the grass toward it.

EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs and a county flatbed climb the dirt drive toward the barn.

In the lead SUV a phone sits in a dashboard mount, a call running on speaker. ADMINISTRATOR J. PELL -- 50s, pressed collar, a lanyard he keeps touching -- rides in the passenger seat.

BOSS (RADIO):
I need one on the books by Saturday, Pell. A real one, serial number and all. You miss it, they fold your office into Lincoln and I quit taking your calls.

PELL:
You'll have it.

Pell taps the phone dark. He flips the visor down and checks his hair in the little mirror.

He steps out of the SUV already smiling.

Movers in gray coveralls drop the flatbed ramp. A steel dolly rolls off it.

WADE HALVERSEN -- mid-40s, county deputy, hat already off and in his hand -- hangs back by the second truck and doesn't start toward the barn.

At the barn door stands CRICKET DAWES -- 79, seed-corn cap, hands loose at his sides. He doesn't come out to meet them.

Behind him in the dim wait three old men among the folding chairs. DUTCH, STITCH, and GUNNY. None of them sit down.

PELL:
Mr. Dawes. Morning. And thank you, real sincerely, for your patience with all this.

Cricket says nothing. Pell tips his head back at the rafters.

PELL:
They built these to last, didn't they. You'd pay a fortune for joinery like this over on the continent.

Pell clicks his pen and starts down the sheet on his clipboard.

PELL:
(reading)
Alright. One altitude indicator—

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell marks the correction without a word.

PELL:
Noted.

A mover presses an orange sticker to the panel and smooths it flat with his thumb. LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD -- EX-NASA ASSET RECOVERY.

CRICKET:
It was surplus. Nineteen seventy-five. Told it'd be scrapped otherwise.

PELL:
(not looking up)
Paperwork says otherwise.

A mover carries a strap across the farmhouse porch for a shortcut. His boots leave gray scuffs in paint that went on this week.

Pell drifts to the back wall and slides one notebook off the shelf. He fans three pages of grid-ruled block printing.

PELL:
Personal papers.

He turns a page, then sets the notebook back crooked on the shelf.

PELL:
No salvage value. Leave them.

A mover works a bolt at the base of the cradle and skins his knuckle. He shakes his hand and looks over at the pegboard.

Cricket lifts the right socket off the board and holds it out. The man takes it and can't bring himself to look up.

CRICKET:
(quiet and hard)
Not one of you ever built a thing out here. Now it's all yours.

Pell stops writing. He looks at Cricket for the first time.

PELL:
You didn't build this either, Mr. Dawes. Nineteen seventy-five it should've gone back to NASA, and it never did, and for fifty years nobody so much as asked. You just had it a long time. Long enough it started to feel like yours.

Cricket doesn't answer him.

The dolly rolls toward the door with the crew couch strapped down on it.

Cricket steps into the doorway and plants himself square in it, feet set, hands at his sides.

The movers stop. Nobody moves.

PELL:
(to Wade)
Deputy.

Wade comes across the yard slow, hat still in his hand.

CRICKET:
You'll have to move me, Wade.

WADE:
(low)
Earl. Federal list came down Tuesday. County don't see a dime off any of it. Nobody does.

Behind Cricket, Stitch shifts a half step forward.

STITCH:
Where's it headed.

WADE:
(to Stitch)
Warehouse outside Lincoln, is what I hear. Same one as the rest of it.
(to Cricket)
There's a window to appeal it. It's open till four.

Wade takes Cricket's arm with both hands. He doesn't say anything but the name.

WADE:
Earl.

He walks Cricket three steps to the side. Cricket lets him. His eyes never leave the couch.

The dolly rolls past the two of them, through the door, and down the ramp.

Pell tucks the clipboard under his arm and turns to the men left standing in the yard.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But as the Accord reminds us -- harmony is a verb.

He gets in the SUV. The two trucks and the flatbed pull down the drive, and the dust hangs a while and settles.

Inside the barn, where the trainer stood, a clean rectangle shows on the concrete, four bright bolt holes at its corners.

Cricket walks to the edge of it and stops.

He presses one hand hard to the back of his neck. One breath. Then he straightens up.

On the workbench sits an old two-way radio the movers never listed.

Dutch, Stitch, and Gunny come in from the yard and stand along the edge of the dust with him.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Wednesday.

GUNNY:
We'll be here.

STITCH:
I'll bring the pot.

DUTCH:
Nineteen hundred, then.

Cricket reaches up and pulls the cord on the work light. It drops a circle of light on the bare concrete.
